pullRequest.body:
This PR defines an instance of `MonoidalClosed` on `C ⥤ Type max w v u` where `C : Type u` with `[Category.{v} C]`, and `w` is an arbitrary universe. An explicit internal hom functor is constructed, and is proved to be a right adjoint to `tensorLeft`.

---

Same here (and another one a few lines below)

I'm a little confused. We checked earlier that the monoidal structure being used above came from the "chosen" cartesian structure, but this suggests that you're looking at the "noncomputable" version coming from existence of finite products in the sense of `limit`. Can you check that the code above (especially `adj`) is indeed using the chosen cartesian structure?

As far as I can tell everything uses the "chosen" cartesian structure. I am checking in the same way as earlier, by seeing if `(F ⊗ G).obj c = ((F.obj c) × (G.obj c))` is true by `rfl`. It seems to be true in the context of `adj`.

I see what's happening now. The code you have could be problematic because there are two monoidal instances around. I would just make a `MonoidalClosed` instance instead. The point is that `CartesianClosed` is defined as:
```lean
abbrev CartesianClosed (C : Type u) [Category.{v} C] [HasFiniteProducts C] :=
  MonoidalClosed C
```
In your case, you have a monoidal structure coming from `ChosenFiniteProducts`, and now you're putting another monoidal structure using the noncomputable products. So, I would ignore `CartesianClosed` altoghether and just go with `MonoidalClosed`.
Ok, I guess `CartesianClosed` can be worked out later, if at all

For the applications to simplicial categories (showing that simplicial objects in `C` is a simplicial category, not just `C := Type u`), I think we should do a more general construction:
```lean
import Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Functor.Category
import Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Types
import Mathlib.CategoryTheory.Yoneda

universe w v' v u u'

namespace CategoryTheory.Functor

variable {C : Type u} [Category.{v} C] {D : Type u'} [Category.{v'} D]

variable (K L : C ⥤ D)

-- if this made sense, this would be the type of `A ⊗ K ⟶ L`
structure Hom₂ (A : C ⥤ Type w) where
  app (X : C) (a : A.obj X) : K.obj X ⟶ L.obj X
  naturality {X Y : C} (φ : X ⟶ Y) (a : A.obj X) :
    K.map φ ≫ app Y (A.map φ a) = app X a ≫ L.map φ := by aesop_cat

-- if this made sense, this would be the functor which sends `A : C ⥤ Type w` to the type `A ⊗ K ⟶ L`
def hom₂Functor : (C ⥤ Type w)ᵒᵖ ⥤ Type (max u v' w) where
  obj A := Hom₂ K L A.unop
  map {A A'} f x :=
    { app := fun X a ↦ x.app X (f.unop.app _ a)
      naturality := fun {X Y} φ a ↦ by
        dsimp
        rw [← Hom₂.naturality]
        congr 2
        exact congr_fun (f.unop.naturality φ) a }

def ihom : C ⥤ Type (max u v v') := coyoneda.rightOp ⋙ hom₂Functor.{v} K L

example {E : Type u'} [Category.{max u v} E] (F G : C ⥤ E) : C ⥤ Type (max u v) := ihom F G

example {C' : Type} [SmallCategory C'] (F G : C' ⥤ D) : C' ⥤ Type v' := ihom F G

example (F G : C ⥤ Type (max u v)) : C ⥤ Type (max u v) := ihom F G

example (F G : C ⥤ Type (max u v w)) : C ⥤ Type (max u v w) := ihom F G

end CategoryTheory.Functor
```

Unless there is an obvious mistake, this should be isomorphic to your `ihom`. (Not sure about the names I have randomly chosen above...)

It would be great if we could avoid introducing `ulift` in the definitions.
Then, using the second example, this `ihom` applied to two simplicial objects will give a simplicial set. (This construction is analogous to `presheafHom` in `Sites.SheafHom`.)
Thanks Joël, I remember now that you already spoke to me about doing things this way. This does seem better to me. I guess I'll work on proving the adjunction with this definition of `ihom` instead.
Does automation work directly if `functorHomEquiv`, `Functor.functorHomEquiv`, and `homObjEquiv` are tagged with `@[simps]`/`@[simps!]`? Are there any drawbacks to this?

Automation makes `adj` a lot shorter if I add `@[simps]` /`@[simps!]` to `functorHomEquiv`, `Functor.functorHomEquiv`, `homObjEquiv`, but also `rightAdj`, `rightAdj_map` and `homObjFunctor`. The first 3 suffice to remove `left_triangle_components`, and the last 3 seem necessary to remove `right_triangle_components`. I'm not sure of any drawbacks to this.
